<TITLE> US welcomes Taiwan moves to stop human trafficking </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 TAIPEI, June 13 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The US State Department has taken Taiwan off a list of regions being watched as hotspots for human trafficking and harsh treatment of migrant workers. Taipei had faced the prospect of sanctions if it remained on the list, but over the past year the government had approved a broad plan to tackle trafficking, toughened visa rules and prosecuted more violators, the State Department said. "In 2006, it was evident that the Taiwan authorities increased efforts to prosecute, convict and punish traffickers," said its annual Trafficking in Persons Report, released late on Tuesday. "Taiwan authorities made modest progress in protecting victims of trafficking, though overall protections remained inadequate." Half the 340,000 foreign workers in Taiwan are private servants or nurses not protected by labour laws, the report said. Some Chinese and Southeast Asian workers have entered the relatively well-off island by obtaining fake marriages or with the help of labour brokers who scam or mistreat migrants. Smuggling in prostitutes also remains a problem, the report added
